article.description: Sidney Spencer sank a 3-pointer with 1:18 left in overtime and Kiesha Brown added four free throws and a steal in the closing seconds to give the Los Angeles Sparks a 98-93 victory over the Connecticut Sun on Friday night.
article.headline: Sparks use balanced offensive effort to top Suns
article.linkText: Spencer's 3-pointer helps Sparks seal OT victory
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sidney Spencer sank a 3-pointer with 1:18 left in overtime and Kiesha Brown added four free throws and a steal in the closing seconds to give the Los Angeles Sparks a 98-93 victory over the Connecticut Sun on Friday night.

Brown tied her career high with 11 assists, Lisa Leslie had 22 points and 10 rebounds, DeLisha Milton-Jones scored 20 points, Marie Ferdinand-Harris 19 and Candace Parker 17 for the Sparks (6-2), who have won four of five.

"I got 11 assists because they made shots," Brown said of her teammates. "We knew we had the advantage in the post. We've got three really good low-post players (Leslie, Jones and Parker), we just want to take advantage of it. It's just a matter of will and heart."

Lindsay Whalen had 20 points, seven rebounds and four steals to lead the Sun (8-2), whose five-game winning streak ended. Asjha Jones and Tamika Whitmore added 18 points apiece.

"Unlike when we played Phoenix and went overtime against Indiana, we didn't lose our composure," Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. "That was very big for us."

Connecticut, which trailed by 14 points in the first quarter, led 93-91 before Spencer made a 3 to put Los Angeles ahead by one.

"Candace set a great screen, and DeLisha found me," Spencer said. "They have to respect Candace, so (the Sun) was kind of late on the defensive switch. It just left me open."

Brown stole the ball with 22.9 seconds left, got fouled by Whalen, and made two free throws with 18.9 seconds to go.

After Milton-Jones tipped a rebound off Whitmore, Brown got fouled by Whitmore and made two more free throws with 0.7 seconds remaining.

The Sparks led 87-83 with 1:52 left in regulation, but Whalen made two shots in a 35-second span to forge an 87-87 tie with a minute to go.

"It's one of those games you walk away from going, 'woulda, coulda, shoulda,'" Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "They need to understand that little things beat you. I didn't like some of our defensive breakdowns."
